}}
He then went to the Presidential Palace in central Yogyakarta, where the government leaders were discussing an ultimatum which stated that the city would be stormed unless the leadership accepted colonial rule. Sudirman urged that the president and vice-president leave the city and fight as guerrillas, actions they had previously promised, but this suggestion was rejected. Although his doctors forbade it, Sudirman received permission from Sukarno to join his men. The central government evacuated to the [[Kraton Ngayogyakarta Hadiningrat]] at the urging of Sultan [[Hamengkubuwana&nbsp;IX]], but were captured and exiled.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=92–95}}{{sfn|Said|1991|p=99}}

===Guerrilla warfare===
Sudirman first went to his official home and gathered sensitive documents, which he burned to prevent them falling into Dutch hands.{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=57}} His convoy, consisting of Sudirman, a small group of soldiers, and his personal doctor, then made their way south, towards Kretek, Parangtritis, [[Bantul]]. There they were received by the district head at 18:00. After several days in Kretek, during which time Sudirman sent undercover troops into the Dutch-occupied city for reconnaissance and to ask his wife for jewellery to sell and help fund the guerrilla movement, he and his group travelled east along the south coast to [[Wonogiri Regency|Wonogiri]].{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=97–99}} Before the Dutch attack it had already been decided that Sudirman would be able to better control the guerrillas from eastern Java, where there were still several bases.{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=58}} Meanwhile, Alfiah and the children were ordered to stay in the Kraton.{{sfn|Jakarta City Government, Sudirman}} Aware that he was being pursued by the Dutch, on 23 December Sudirman ordered his troops to continue to [[Ponorogo]], where they stopped at the home of Mahfuz, a [[kyai]] and [[ulama|Islamic religious leader]]; Mahfuz gave the general a cane to help him walk, although Sudirman was, and continued to be, carried on a [[Litter (vehicle)|litter]]. They then continued east.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=100–101}}

[[File:Sudirman resting with guerillas, Kota Jogjakarta 200 Tahun, plate before page 65.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A crowd of men, with their leader in the middle|300px|Sudirman, surrounded by his guerrillas during their campaign]]
Outside of [[Trenggalek]], Sudirman and his group were stopped by TNI soldiers belonging to 102&nbsp;Battalion.{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=61}} These soldiers, who were told that Sudirman&nbsp;– who was in civilian clothes and unrecognised by the troops holding them&nbsp;– was a prisoner, refused to allow the group to pass;{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=102–105}} they were suspicious as Sudirman's convoy carried maps and notes on Indonesian military movements, things which may have belonged to spies.{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=62}} When the group's commander, Major Zainal Fanani, came to check the situation, he realised that Sudirman was with them and apologised. Told that his men were right to guard their areas diligently, Fanani called a post in [[Kediri Regency|Kediri]] and ordered that a car be sent to pick up the general and his troops. After a time in Kediri, they continued further east; as they left the city on 24&nbsp;December, Dutch planes attacked Kediri.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=102–105}}

The constant Dutch attacks led Sudirman, perhaps at the suggestion of one of his men, to change his clothes and give his old outfit to one of his soldiers, Second Lieutenant Heru Kesser&nbsp;– who bore a resemblance to Sudirman.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=102–105}}{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=64}}{{sfn|Setiadi|Yuliawati|2012|p=28}} Kesser was ordered to head south with a large company of soldiers, remove the clothes, and furtively return north, while Sudirman waited in Karangnongko. The diversion was successful, and on 27&nbsp;December Sudirman and his men made their way to Jambu Village. Arriving on 9&nbsp;January 1949, Sudirman met with several government ministers who had not been present during the Dutch attack on Yogyakarta: [[Supeno]], Susanto Tirtoprojo, and Susilowati. With the politicians, Sudirman made his way to Banyutuwo, ordering some of his soldiers to linger back and hold off Dutch ground troops. In Banyutuwo, they held for over a week. However, on 21&nbsp;January, when Dutch forces approached the village, Sudirman and his entourage were forced to leave, fighting their way out in heavy rain.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=102–105}}

Sudirman and his troops continued to make their way through the jungles and forests, eventually arriving at Sobo, near [[Mount Lawu]], on 18&nbsp;February. During the journey, Sudirman used a radio set to convey orders to local TNI troops if he believed that the region was secure. Feeling weaker because of the physical hardships he had faced, including travelling through the forests and a lack of food, and believing the area to be safe, Sudirman decided that Sobo would serve as his guerrilla headquarters.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=106–107}}{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=65}} The local commander, Lieutenant Colonel Wiliater Hutagalung, served as his go-between with the other TNI leaders. Aware that international opinion, which was beginning to condemn Dutch actions in Indonesia, could bring Indonesia greater recognition, Sudirman and Hutagalung discussed possible terms of action, before agreeing on a large-scale assault.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=108–110}} Meanwhile, the Dutch began to spread propaganda claiming that they had captured Sudirman; this claim was intended to break the morale of the guerrillas.{{sfn|KR 1950, Djenderal Sudirman Wafat}}{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=138}}

Sudirman ordered Hutagalung to begin planning a full-scale assault, in which TNI soldiers&nbsp;– in uniform&nbsp;– would attack the Dutch and show their strength in front of foreign reporters and United Nations investigative teams. Hutagalung, together with officers under his commander Colonel Bambang Sugeng and government officials under Governor [[Wongsonegoro]], spent several days discussing ways to ensure the attack could be successful.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=108–110}} The discussion may have resulted in the General Offensive of 1&nbsp;March 1949, which saw TNI soldiers attack Dutch outposts throughout central Java. Troops under Lieutenant Colonel [[Suharto]] retook Yogyakarta for six hours before withdrawing, a successful [[show of force]] which caused the Dutch to lose face internationally; they had previously declared the TNI eradicated.{{sfn|Adi|2011|pp=108–110}}{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=74}} However, who truly ordered the offensive remains uncertain: Suharto and Hamengkubuwana&nbsp;IX claimed responsibility, while Bambang Sugeng's brother reportedly overheard him ordering the assault.{{sfn|Said|1991|pp=126–127}}

[[File:Sukarno hugging Sudirman, Kota Jogjakarta 200 Tahun, plate after page 80.jpg|thumb|alt=Two men embracing|Sudirman (left) being embraced by President [[Sukarno]] upon his return to Yogyakarta.]]
Under increased pressure from the United Nations, on 7&nbsp;May 1949 Dutch–Indonesian negotiations resulted in the Roem-Royen Agreement, a controversial measure which guaranteed Dutch withdrawal from Yogyakarta, among other points;{{efn|This agreement was initially opposed by both the Dutch and Indonesian militaries but ultimately passed {{harv|Said|1991|pp=116–118}}.}}{{sfn|Said|1991|pp=116–118}} The Dutch withdrawal commenced in late June, and the Indonesian leadership began returning to Yogyakarta from exile in early July. Sukarno ordered Sudirman to return to Yogyakarta as well, but Sudirman refused to let the Dutch withdraw without a fight; he considered the TNI to now be strong enough to defeat the dispirited Dutch. Although he was promised medicine and support in Yogyakarta, Sudirman refused to return to the political leadership, whom he considered acquiescent to the Dutch. He only agreed to return after receiving a letter, although sources disagree on its sender.{{efn|{{harvtxt|Said|1991|p=119}} writes that the letter was sent by Hamengkubuwana&nbsp;IX and delivered by Suharto, while {{harvtxt|Imran|1980|pp=75–80}} credit a letter from Sudirman's subordinate and close friend, Colonel [[Gatot Soebroto]].}} On 10 July, Sudirman and his group returned to Yogyakarta, where they were greeted by thousands of civilians and warmly received by the political elite there.{{sfn|Imran|1980|pp=75–80}}{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=199}} The reporter [[Rosihan Anwar]], who was present when the letter was delivered, wrote in 1973 that "Sudirman had to return to Yogyakarta to avoid any perceptions of a rift among the republic's top leaders".{{sfn|Setiadi|Yuliawati|2012|p=47}}

==Post-war and death==
In early August Sudirman approached Sukarno and asked him to continue the guerrilla war; Sudirman did not expect the Dutch to abide by the Roem-Royen Agreement, based on the failings of the previous agreements. Sukarno disagreed, which was a blow to Sudirman. When Sudirman threatened to resign his post, blaming the government's inconsistency for his tuberculosis and Oerip's death in November 1948, Sukarno threatened to do so as well.{{sfn|Jakarta City Government, Sudirman}}{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=129}}{{sfn|Jakarta City Government, Oerip Soemohardjo}} As he thought that such a resignation would have a destabilising effect, Sudirman stayed his hand,{{sfn|Imran|1980|pp=82–83}} and a Java-wide cease fire came into effect on 11&nbsp;August 1949.{{sfn|Said|1991|p=122}}

Continuing to suffer from tuberculosis, Sudirman was checked into Panti Rapih hospital,{{sfn|Imran|1980|pp=82–83}} where he stayed until October, when he was transferred to a sanatorium in nearby Pakem.{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=203}} As a result of his illness, Sudirman made few public appearances.{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=84}}{{sfn|KR 1950, Pak Dirman Istirahat}}{{sfn|KR 1950, Perdjalanan Terachir}} Sudirman was transferred to a home in Magelang in December.{{sfn|KR 1950, Magelang Berkabung}} In the meantime, the Indonesian and Dutch governments held a [[Dutch–Indonesian Round Table Conference|several-month-long conference]] which resulted in Dutch recognition of Indonesian sovereignty on 27&nbsp;December 1949.{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=83}} Sudirman, despite his illness, was reconfirmed that day as commander-in-chief of the TNI, now serving the newly established [[Republic of the United States of Indonesia]]. On 28&nbsp;December, Jakarta once again became the nation's capital.{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=203}}

[[File:Sudirman's casket carried, Kenang-Kenangan Pada Panglima Besar Letnan Djenderal Soedirman, p13.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A line of men carrying a casket|Sudirman's casket being carried by soldiers]]
Sudirman died in Magelang at 18:30 on 29&nbsp;January 1950; this was reported in a special broadcast over RRI.{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=84}} Upon receiving news of his death, the Sudirman family home received numerous visitors, including the entirety of the 9th&nbsp;Brigade, which was stationed nearby.{{sfn|KR 1950, Magelang Berkabung}} The following morning Sudirman's body was brought to Yogyakarta. As the funeral convoy passed, led by four [[tank]]s and consisting of eighty motor vehicles,{{sfn|KR 1950, Perdjalanan Terachir}} thousands of mourners stood at the sides of the streets. The convoy was organised by members of the 9th&nbsp;Brigade.{{sfn|KR 1950, Magelang Berkabung}}

The [[viewing (funeral)|viewing]], held at the Great Mosque of Yogyakarta in the afternoon, was attended by numerous political and military elite from both Indonesia and foreign countries; this included Prime Minister [[Abdul Halim (Indonesia)|Abdul Halim]], Minister of Defence Hamengkubuwana&nbsp;IX, Minister of Health [[Johannes Leimena]], Minister of Justice [[Abdoel Gaffar Pringgodigdo]], Minister of Information Arnold Mononutu, Chief of the Air Force Soerjadi Soerjadarma, Colonel Paku Alam&nbsp;VIII, and Suharto. The viewing was closed with a [[Three-volley salute|24-gun salute]].{{sfn|KR 1950, Perdjalanan Terachir}} Sudirman's body was brought to [[Kusumanegara Heroes' Cemetery|Semaki Heroes' Cemetery]] on foot, with a crowd of mourners {{convert|2|km|sp=br}} long trailing behind.{{sfn|KR 1950, Perdjalanan Terachir}} He was interred next to Oerip, after another gun salute. His wife filled in the first scoop of dirt,{{sfn|Imran|1980|p=86}} followed by the government ministers.{{sfn|KR 1950, Perdjalanan Terachir}} The national government ordered flags to be flown at [[half-mast]] throughout the country,{{sfn|KR 1950, Pak Dirman Istirahat}} and Sudirman was promoted to full general.{{sfn|KR 1950, Djenderal Sudirman Wafat}} Major-General [[Tahi Bonar Simatupang]] was selected as the new leader of the armed forces.{{sfn|KR 1950, Perdjalanan Terachir}} Sudirman's memoirs were published later that year; a series of his speeches were also published in 1970.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=127}}

==Legacy==
[[File:Grave of Sudirman.JPG|thumb|right|alt=A grave with the text Sudirman on it|Sudirman's grave at [[Kusumanegara Heroes' Cemetery|Semaki Heroes' Cemetery]] in Yogyakarta; it has become a [[ziyarat|pilgrimage]] destination.]]
An obituary in the Yogyakarta-based daily ''[[Kedaulatan Rakyat|Kedaulatan Rakjat]]'' wrote that Indonesia had lost a "brave and true hero".{{efn|Original: "''... seorang pahlawan jang djudjur dan berani''"}}{{sfn|KR 1950, Pak Dirman Istirahat}} Colonel [[Paku Alam&nbsp;VIII]], in charge of the Yogyakarta area, told the national news agency [[Antara (news agency)|Antara]] that all Indonesians, especially the armed forces, had "lost a father figure who did uncountable deeds for his country".{{efn|Original: "''... seluruh rakjat Indonesia umumnja dan angkatan perang chususnja, kehilangan seorang bapak jg tidak ternilai djasa2nja kepada tanah air ...''"}}{{sfn|KR 1950, Djenderal Sudirman Wafat}} The Indonesian Muslim leader [[Hamka|Haji Abdul Malik Karim Amrullah]], writing soon after Sudirman's death, described the general as a "symbol of the strength of spirit shown by Indonesian heroes,"{{efn|Original: "'' ... lambang dari kebangunan djiwa pahlawan Indonesia.''"}}{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=218}} while the Muslim politician [[Muhammad Isa Anshary]] described Sudirman as a "son of the revolution, as he was born in the revolution, and raised by the revolution."{{efn|Original: "''Putera revolusi, karena dia lahir dalam revolusi, dan dibesarkan oleh revolusi.}}{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=219}} In a radio speech, Hatta described Sudirman as impossible to control and hard-headed, but ultimately intent on doing what was right for the country; Hatta noted that, although Sudirman often did not like the government's position, he would generally obey his orders.{{sfn|KR 1950, Djenderal Sudirman Wafat}} However, Hamengkubuwana&nbsp;IX noted that KNIL trained soldiers such as Abdul Haris Nasution and Tahi Bonar Simatupang were disappointed in Sudirman because of his background and poor knowledge of military techniques.{{sfn|Said|1991|p=55}}

Modern opinions in Indonesia tend to be laudatory. Sardiman, a professor of history at [[Universitas Negeri Yogyakarta|Yogyakarta State University]], writes that Sudirman was as lively a speaker as Sukarno, who was known for his fiery speeches,{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=93}} and a devoted, incorruptible leader.{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=174}} The Indonesian historian and former Minister of Education and Culture [[Nugroho Notosusanto]] described Sudirman as "his only idol", citing the general's guerrilla period as the origin of the army's ''[[esprit de corps]]''.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=128}} The general's guerrilla campaign is emphasised in biographies of him because, during that period, the army had a greater role than the exiled political leadership;{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=128}} beginning in the 1970s, all military cadets had to retrace the {{convert|100|km|adj=on}} long route prior to graduation, a "pilgrimage" meant to instill a sense of struggle.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=130}} Sudirman's grave is also a [[ziyarat|pilgrimage]] destination, both for the military and general public.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=133}} According to Katharine McGregor of the [[University of Melbourne]], the Indonesian military has elevated Sudirman to a saint-like status.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=220}}

Sudirman received numerous [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Indonesia|awards from the national government]] posthumously, including the Bintang Sakti, Bintang Gerilya,{{sfn|Tjokropranolo|1992|p=327}} Bintang Mahaputera Adipurna,{{sfn|Indonesian State Secretariat, Bintang Mahaputera Adipurna}} Bintang Mahaputera Pratama,{{sfn|Indonesian State Secretariat, Bintang Mahaputera Pratama}} Bintang Republik Indonesia Adipurna,{{sfn|Indonesian State Secretariat, Bintang Republik Indonesia Adipurna}} and Bintang Republik Indonesia Adipradana.{{efn|The Bintang Sakti is a high-level military award for showing bravery above and beyond the call of duty {{harv|UU No. 20/2009|pp=4, 10, 23}}. The Bintang Mahaputera is a high-level award for persons who have aided Indonesia's development, become experts in a certain field, or are widely recognised for their sacrifices for the country {{harv|UU No. 20/2009|pp=4, 9, 23}}. The Bintang Republik Indonesia is the highest award available for civilians {{harv|Saragih 2012, SBY bestows honors}}.}}{{sfn|Indonesian State Secretariat, Bintang Republik Indonesia Adipradana}} On 10 December 1964 Sudirman was declared a [[National Hero of Indonesia]] by Presidential Decree 314 of 1964. Oerip was declared a National Hero by the same decree.{{sfn|Indonesian State Secretariat, Daftar Nama Pahlawan}} He was promoted to [[Jenderal Besar|General of the Army]] in 1997.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=139}}

[[File:Indonesia 1968 5r o.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A 5 rupiah banknote, with a picture of Sudirman on its left side|Sudirman on a 5 [[rupiah]] banknote, issued in 1968]]
According to McGregor, the military increasingly used Sudirman's image as a symbol of leadership as it gained more political power.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=127}} An image of Sudirman was featured on every denomination of the 1968 series of [[Indonesian rupiah|rupiah]].{{efn|This included the 1, 2.5, 5, 10, 25, 50, 100, 500, and 1000 rupiah bills {{harv|Cuhaj|2012|pp=501–502}}.}}{{sfn|Cuhaj|2012|pp=501–502}} He featured as a major character in several war films, including ''[[Janur Kuning]]'' (''Yellow Coconut Leaf''; 1979) and ''[[Serangan Fajar]]'' (''Dawn Attack''; 1982).{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=127}}

Numerous museums have been dedicated to Sudirman. His childhood home in [[Purbalingga]] is now the Sudirman Museum,{{sfn|Sardiman|2008|p=8}} while his official home in Yogyakarta is now the Sasmitaloka Museum to General Sudirman.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=127}} The house in Magelang where he died is also now the Sudirman Museum, established on 18 May 1967 and containing artefacts belonging to the general.{{sfn|Magelang City Government, Museum Sudirman}} Other museums, including the [[Monument Yogya Kembali]] in Yogyakarta and the [[Satriamandala Museum]] in Jakarta have rooms dedicated to him.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=127}} Numerous streets are named after Sudirman, including a major street in Jakarta;{{sfn|Jakarta City Government, Sudirman}} McGregor states that nearly every city in the country has a General Sudirman Street. Statues and monuments to him are spread throughout the archipelago, most of which were built after 1970.{{sfn|McGregor|2007|p=127}} [[Jenderal Soedirman University]] in Banyumas, established in 1963, is named after him.{{sfn|Jenderal Soedirman University, About UNSOED}}

==Notes==
{{notes
| notes =

{{efn
| name = A
| 24 January 1916 is the date recognised by the Indonesian government. The actual date may be different {{harv|Adi|2011|pp=1–2}}. The historian Solichin Salam, for example, gives 7 February 1912 as Sudirman's date of birth, while fellow historian Yusuf Puar gives 7 September 1912 (quoted in {{harvnb|Said|1991|p=80}}).
